data_raw <- Sys.glob("../04-analysis/screening/presenceabsence_intersection.backup") %>%
  list.files("08a-*", full.names = T) %>% 
  enframe(name = NULL, value = "file_name") %>%
  mutate(file_contents = map(file_name, ~suppressMessages(read_tsv(.x))),
         Database = map(file_name, ~str_split(.x, "_") %>% unlist() %>% tail(8) %>% head(n = 1) %>% as.character) %>% unlist,
         Min_Supp = map(file_name, ~str_split(.x, "_") %>% unlist() %>% tail(7) %>% head(n = 1)) %>% unlist,
         Inds_Frac = map(file_name, ~str_split(.x, "_") %>% unlist() %>% tail(6) %>% head(n = 1) %>% str_replace("fracinds", "") %>% as.numeric) %>% unlist,
         Pops_Frac = map(file_name, ~str_split(.x, "_") %>% unlist() %>% tail(5) %>% head(n = 1) %>% str_replace("fracpops", "") %>% as.numeric) %>% unlist,
         Single_Pops_Dropped = map(file_name, ~str_split(.x, "_") %>% unlist() %>% tail(4) %>% head(n = 1) %>% str_replace("singleindpopsdropped", "") %>% as.logical) %>% unlist,
         Grouping = map(file_name, ~str_split(.x, "_") %>% unlist() %>% tail(3) %>% head(n = 1)) %>% unlist,
         Level = map(file_name, ~str_split(.x, "_") %>% unlist() %>% tail(2) %>% head(n = 1)) %>% unlist,
         Date = map(file_name, ~str_split(.x, "_") %>% unlist() %>% tail(1) %>% head(n = 1)) %>% unlist %>% str_replace(".tsv", "")) %>%
  select(-file_name) %>%
  filter(Date == "20190902",
         !Min_Supp %in% c(0.08, 0.09) ) %>%
  unnest()

We we confirm that increasing our minimum support from 0.04 to 0.07 we remove all combinations including controls, removing potential laboratory control taxa. We see about half of each category being lost to other non-monophyletic assignments when increasing 0.01 to 0.4, however again much fewer assignments changes between 0.04 and 0.07.

Monophyletic Host Combinations 0.04 to 0.07 only.

To get a better feeling of the different types of combination assignments, we can firstly remove the 0.01 category as this is likely consisting a lot of low-abundant taxa (or tail), which in our context will be difficult to separate from noise - either from misassignments from unspecific short reads, damage, or background environmental contamination.

data_minsup_mhcreduced <- data_raw %>%
  filter(!Single_Pops_Dropped,
         Combination %in% c("Pan:Homo", "Gorilla:Pan:Homo", "Alouatta:Gorilla:Pan:Homo", "Alouatta:Gorilla:Pan:Homo:Control"),
         Min_Supp != 0.01) %>%
  select(Database, Combination, Min_Supp, Taxon, Tax_Level)

ggplot(data_minsup_mhcreduced,
       aes(x = Min_Supp, stratum = Combination, alluvium = Taxon,
           label = Combination)) +
  geom_flow(stat = "alluvium",
            color = "darkgray",
            lode.guidance = "zigzag", na.rm = F) +
  geom_stratum(aes(fill = Combination), na.rm = F) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = colours) +
  xlab("Minimum Support Threshold") +
  ylab("Number of Taxa") +
  theme_minimal(base_family = "Roboto", base_size = 7) +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom") +
  facet_wrap(Database ~ Tax_Level, scales = "free_y")

Using our more confident 0.04 and 0.07 categories, we can see there are 2-3 changing of asignments to combinations outside the monophyletic expected combinations, and a few reassignments. We can check more specifically what these are as follows.

data_minsup_mhcreduced %>%
  spread(Min_Supp, Combination) %>%
  filter(`0.04` != `0.07`) %>%
  arrange(Database, Tax_Level)

Here we can see 2 changes for nt genus, 4 for nt species, and 4 for RefSeq genus and 3 for refseq species. All taxa other than Mycobacterium are isolated from the oral cavity. Mycobacterium is a highly diverse environmental taxon. As we do not calculate core with actual abundance (other than filtering by the minimum support value), this likely is retained as core in samples as it is a combination of control and burial environment Mycobacterium reads, rather than being a true oral taxa. The other taxa that are reassigned from a (+control) core to host only - Streptococus, Actinomyces and Corynebacterium are diverse taxa that reside in many parts of the human body. It is likely these alignments are combinations of ancient oral and modern skin contamination, and are reassigned as the lower-abundant skin contamination is removed by increasing to 0.07, leaving the highly abundant oral assignments. As all other taxa are known to be isolated or specfic to the oral cavity this suggests their authenticity. Most changes to the Pan:Homo combination are from anaerobic bacteria (e.g. Tannerella, Treponema, Olsenella) - representative of the stronger signal of these taxa in Homo and Pan vs.  Gorilla and Alouatta which have lower abundances of later colonisers, whereas to Gorilla:Pan:Homo, these are aerobic taxa typically represent early colonisers - which are more prevalent in Gorilla.

Single Population

No difference at species level for both nt and refseq databasee. We do see one change at species and genus level with the nt database.

To identify what change this is

We see in both cases they drop outside our expected mono-phyletic filtering - i.e. they aren’t in Gorilla.

WTF Mycobacterium?

We also note that we have Mycobacterium still being maintained in our nt core.

This is a bit odd as it’s a common environmental contaminant. Indeed, even at 0.04% minimum support it is actually in a core with the controls. Lets see if we can look a little closer at this. Is it also in genus in refseq?

So it seems to be limited to just genus nt. Lets check this.

So that would suggest generally that the actual Mycobacterium assignments, despite being abundant are very diverse, so the the species level assignments are not passing the MinSupport threshold.

We can check this more specifically.

Set aesthetics

To see the overall number of Mycobacterium species level assignments

We indeed see that Mycobacterium is highly prevalent in environmental samples. It is however lower in library controls, which is why it is not picked up in the core-microbiome min-support threshold increase (as in the min support removes most of the alignments in the controls when increased too high, so it is not considered a core to controls when increasing to 0.07 with genus, but is removed at the lower threshold at 0.04 for species).

We can also look at the types of Mycobacterium species that these assignments are derived from.

The highest two sources of Mycobacterium (kansasii, avium) alignments across all individuals are water-borne taxa, again suggesting this is derived from environmental contamination.

We can also see how they are represented in the NCBI genome database (which we use as a proxy for nt).

And plot

We see that avium and kansaii are 2nd and 4th in the highest number of assemblies, suggesting they are likely over-represented in the database.
